The setup right now:
When you built the RDS Proxy, we created two endpoints on it:

The default endpoint (aws_db_proxy.aurora.endpoint) — created automatically, supports read AND write operations.
A read-only endpoint (aws_db_proxy_endpoint.aurora_reader) — the extra one you added specifically, only accepts read operations.

Right now the Lambda's db_endpoint env var points at #2 — the read-only one. That was intentional — the SOAP verification is a lookup (read query), so read-only made sense.
Why the read-only endpoint is breaking:
Look at the Lambda error trace again. When pg8000 (the Postgres library) runs cursor.execute(query), the very first thing it does — before running your actual SELECT — is send this to the database:
sqlBEGIN TRANSACTION
That's how pg8000's default mode works: every operation is wrapped in a transaction, whether it's a read or a write.
The problem: a read-only proxy endpoint doesn't allow transactions to be opened, because a transaction implies you might write. So the moment pg8000 sends BEGIN TRANSACTION, the proxy terminates the connection. That's why you get the very specific error: network error right after execute_simple("begin transaction").
Why switching to the default endpoint fixes it:
The default proxy endpoint (aws_db_proxy.aurora.endpoint) accepts transactions — reads or writes — because it's read/write capable. pg8000's BEGIN TRANSACTION is fine, your SELECT runs, transaction commits, all good.
The honest trade-off you're making:

Read-only endpoint = a small safety guarantee (Lambda literally cannot write, even if there's a bug). But requires the app code to run in autocommit mode (no transactions).
Default endpoint = accepts everything. Slightly less strict, but works with pg8000's default behavior.

For this Lambda, the actual query is a read (SELECT ... FROM ... WHERE VIN = ?). Nothing in the code writes. So switching to the default endpoint isn't giving up any real safety — it's just accepting that you're using the more permissive endpoint.
The alternative (the cleaner but harder path):
Fix it in the code — configure pg8000 to run in autocommit mode so it doesn't open transactions on read queries. Then the read-only endpoint would work. But that's a code change in the Lambda, which is Zach's territory. And it's more work for the same functional outcome.
My honest recommendation, plainly:
Switch to the default proxy endpoint. It's a one-line infra change, unblocks the timing test right now, and doesn't compromise safety for this Lambda's actual use pattern (reads only). The read-only endpoint was over-engineered for a Lambda whose code uses transaction-wrapped queries — it never would have worked without app-side changes.
Longer-term (not now): if the team wants the extra strictness, Zach can make the Lambda run in autocommit mode, and you can switch back to the read-only endpoint in a follow-up PR.
Does that make sense? Once you're comfortable with the reasoning, the fix is:
In lambda.tf, change:
hcldb_endpoint = aws_db_proxy_endpoint.aurora_reader.endpoint
To:
hcldb_endpoint = aws_db_proxy.aurora.endpoint
Push, plan, apply. Then retest.
